is a more accurate figure and for the statisticians to feel that that is properly justifiable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:34pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Jeremy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lefroy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Thank you</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">I would like to turn now to non</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#x2011;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">fiscal</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> spending, i.e. spending </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">that results</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> in an asset on the balance sheet</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The Treasury has asked you, or instructed you, to increase that by £500</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">million in the year</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Is that actually happening?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mark </span><span styl